tomorrow , the employment situation report come out and as usual , there will be idiot claim the government do n't count people not receive unemployment benefit , or that the government be n't count people who should be count etc.
so let 's discuss .
question : what exactly do we want to measure and why ?
answer : we want to measure the labor market and how it be change , especially how difficult it be to get a job .
first difficulty be that not everyone can freely participate in the labor market .
there be law and barrier afffecting group of people .
while children can work , there be significant restriction as to field , hour , change job etc.
at approx age 16 the restriction be go , almost all job be open for full or part time work .
so we ignore anyone under 16 .
next group be prisoner . while some " work " it 's not really a labor market system and work or not work be not free choice of entry and exit .
so we ignore prisoner .
next group be those mentally or physically incapable of work .
while many disable and those with psychological condition do work , those who be institutionalize or in long term care ( such as a hospice ) can n't .
so we ignore those in an institution or long term care .
there remain many disable who can n't work but be n't in an institution , but since some can and some can n't work , there 's no bright line , so we include them all .
next : retirees .
many country exclude those over the age of 65 .
for a country with mandatory retirement , or generous government pension , that be sensible as almost all those over 65 do n't need to work and do n't work and include them can distort the picture .
but in the us , there be no mandatory retirement ( except in military/police ) and retirement benefit be not as generous or universal .
so no maximum age limit for us .
last , military . for a while , they be count as employ ( 1984 @-@ 1994 ) but since there 's no free exit and it 's not a market system , include them just raise the number of employ by a fairly constant level , so it 's better to exclude the military .
so we have our population : the adult civilian non @-@ institutional population .
how do we divide that up ?
the key be to be as objective as possible .
since we have to use a survey ( it 's just not possible to do a full count every month ) , any subjectivity will increase our error , so we have to avoid any possible overlap or judgement call .
let 's look at employ .
who be employ ?
some have suggest a minimum number of hour work , but be that a good idea ?
plenty of people voluntarily work few hour , or in a particular week only work a few hour . should we say they do n't really have a job or be n't really work ?
that 's very subjecive . we do n't want to run into case be someone nomrmally work 40 hour a week , but in the particular week of the survey she only work 2 hour and count as unemployed .
so we set a bright line of 1 hour for pay , and also include those as employ people temporarily absent due to brief illness , injury , vacation , strike , bad weather etc.
we can always look at sub group later .
unpaid labor .
some people do n't get pay ( directly ) for work , either charity work or work on a family farm or family business .
let 's not include charity work , because that 's not really part of the labor market .
but family business @/@ farm be a different story...the person be either just help out , ( mean if they do n't already have another job they would n't take one if they be n't work for family and @/@ or no one would have to be hire in their place ) or they be a substantial part of the business prevent them from another job and fill a job slot no one else can take .
so let 's set a bright line of 15 hour a week and anyone work without pay on family business farm 15 hour or more a week be employ .
what about someone hire but not yet work ?
many thing can happen , so we won't call them employ until they 're actually work .
now for the unemployed .
in casual usage , this can mean many different thing , but what we want be a precise , objective definition .
and what we 're look for be available worker who be n't work .
this have an impact on the labor market..supply over demand .
some people do n't want to work...retirees , housewives/husbands , full time student , and some people on drug or alcohol or criminal or lazy .
so let 's not count anyone who do n't want a job .
should we count everyone who say they want a job ?
they could be lie .
they could be unable to take a job if offer ( mean they 're not available labor ) .
so what bright line can we set ?
if someone be actually look for work , send a resume , go to an interview , on the union list , then we can safely assume that they be really available for work .
but if someone be n't do anything about a get a job , then they 're not available , anymore than someone who do n't want to work .
sure they may still consider themselves " unemployed " and they may sincerely want to work , but since they 're not available , since they 're not part of the actual supply of labor and can n't be hire , we exclude them .
so we have our employ , we have our unemployed....this be our labor force , our available supply of people who can work or be hire .
everyone else be not in the labor force .
since the population tend to grow , for an historical comparison , it 's better to look at rates/ratios/percentages to get a clearer picture .
labor force participation rate : the labor force as a percent of the population .
this can be largely affect by non @-@ economic factor as the increase of women into the labor force in the 60 s and 70 s show , but it give a good look at how much of the population be try to work .
employment @-@ population ratio : this tell us the percent of the population that 's actually work .
again , non @-@ economic factor play a role but look at the change can tell us useful thing .
unemployment rate : unemployed as a percent of the labor force .
this tell us how much of available labor...people willing and able and available to work... be not be use .
this be all economic factors...the percent of people try and fail to get a job .
do this give a complete picture of the labor market ?
of course not...it 's not meant to .
it do n't tell us type of job , if people be work as much as they want to , people who do n't believe they would be successful .
but it tell us what we 're look for : the percent of people who we know for sure cannot get a job .
i think that explain the basics .
i 'll be happy to clarify question or discuss any real issue .
