or you can do actual analysis of the data .
" job " come from the current employment statistic survey ( ces ) while unemployment ( and total employment ) come from the current population survey ( cps ) .
the ces be non @-@ farm payroll employment . it exclude agriculture , the self @-@ employ , unpaid family worker and private employee ( private cook , nanny , maid , etc ) .
so " job " may go up 150k , but total employment go up 300k .
you can n't directly compare 2 measure that measure different thing .
much of the drop in ue have be for the wrong reasons...a decrease labor force .
that be not the case for the january drop .
at best thing have be spotty lately...up and down .
you can n't just look at one number or one measure and say " thing be good " or " thing be bad ."
the best unit of measure be , i think to determine how many americans be work .
