we be probably all familiar with the traditional say regard suicide - that it be a " coward 's way out ."
my question be this : be it really ? or be it the opposite ?
that be , do the act of suicide actually require courage to commit ?
personally i believe it require a tremendous amount of courage and perhaps the greatest amount of courage of any possible action .
after all , we be speak of terminate one 's own life , perhaps forever end one 's existence .
we all have our thought on what come next , but no one can be certain .
one may be forever end his existence , or he may be forever subject himself to punishment if the religious view on suicide be a sin be correct .
either way though , one be enter the unknown by willingly terminate his life , which blatantly violate the biological drive to live , to continue exist .
how can this not be an extremely courageous act , much more so that " find the courage to remain alive in the face of unbeatable problem ? "
remain alive to face one 's problem be continue the state of existence that one have always know .
end that life be journey into something new , something that may be better or may be worse than the current state of existence the individual be comfortably familiar with .
either way he be terminate his life and accept the state of death that deep down we all fear .
how can one consider voluntarily enter that state cowardly ?
