yes , although i 'd like to see a change from first past the post to proportional representation .
also , to the op , i 'm pretty sure that there be hardly any hereditary peer leave in the house of lord
it absolutely be a democratic country .
we have an elect house of common which be sovereign .
people point to the inherit monarchy and the llife peerage as sign of not be democratic , but ignore one significant thing :
many other democratic country worldwide do not elect their head of state or their upper house .
for example : germany , italy , canada , australia , japan , holland , spain , belgium , sweden , norway , denmark , czech republic , hungary , greece and many others do not elect the head of state .
likewise , ireland , canada , germany , france , holland , jamaica and many others do not elect their upper house - at least not directly .
as long as the elect portion of the state ( i.e . the house of common ) have supreme power , then the democratic imperative be satisfy .
ironically , have other portion of the state elect will invite deadlock and compromise , and the democratic will of the people will be drown out in the politicking that will go on .
the lord increase democracy in the uk - it 's a safeguard .
firslty the chamber , although it have party politics , be keep in balance so it be not as partisan as the common .
secondly it be a chamber of expert which function in a largely advisory capacity .
thirdly these guy be lifer , which mean they be able to think past the next election for the good of the country .
