curious...do other earthquake agency agree with the data from tokyo ?
i would like to know what scale they 're use , because different seismic scale can result in enormously different result .
a perfect example be the two largest christchurch earthquake .
the first be m7+ but do only minor damage and cause no fatality due to a low mercalli intensity read ( actual measure of intensity of shake in a particular place ) .
the second m6.3 quake register at x ( intense ) and higher on the mercalli intensity scale and have the highest peak ground acceleration ever record .
many seismologist have say that the quake would have completely flatten almost any city in the world .
in term of energy release , the deadly christchurch quake be not particularly big , but in term of shake intensity it be one of the most destructive quake ever record .
japan 's " shindo " scale be like the mercalli intensity scale , but do n't have anywhere near as many division .
the highest category be 7 which seem to equate with viii on the mercalli scale ( it go up to xii ) .
this basically mean a scale 7 quake could be anything from a decently size but not overly destructive quake right up to a city @-@ leveling event .
