i hear all sort of perspective on marriage . those who think monogamy be the proper standard , those who think monogamy be a tool use to oppress women , those who think that polygamy be terrible , those who think that polygamy be natural , etc.
but virtually ever culture in the world have some form of marriage...a concept in which a life @-@ long union be idealize , where there be formal ceremony to ' sanctify ' a man and a woman ( or multiple thereof ) . culture where , from childhood , children be raise and teach these ideal to the point where most of us think it be a natural part of human nature .
the form of marriage may differ from culture to culture , but it be consistent throughout our culture .
that be , except for at least one very unique culture , the mosuo , a chinese minority group who live in the himalayan mountain , close to the border with tibet .
two year ago , i establish a non @-@ profit organization to work with the mosuo , focusing on a variety of aspect ( education , development , etc.), but also on promote awareness of their culture , and to try to preserve it .
in the mosuo culture , there be no marriage .
no marriage ceremony exist .
there be no expectation whatsoever of life @-@ time bond or pairings .
children be raise not only without an expectation of spend their life with that one special person , but they often do n't even know ( or care ) who their biological father be .
in the mosuo culture , men and women can change and choose partner as they please .
monogamy be not consider special or even particularly desirable .
the mosuo live in large extended family , with many generation ( grandparent , parent , children , grandchildren , etc.) all live together in the same house .
men sleep in communal sleep room ( they do n't have private bedroom ) ; only the women have the luxury of a private bedroom .
thus , women tend to the the one in control of relationship .
traditionally , a mosuo woman will invite a man to spend the night with her .
the man will come to her home at night , sneak in through her window ( it be also a part of the mosuo culture that , while everyone know this be happen , it should be do in a manner that be not obvious ) , spend the night , and then leave early the next morning before everyone wake up .
thus the term " walk marriage "...because the men must walk to and from their assign rendevous each night .
the mosuo walk marriage be generally the most interesting -- and misunderstood -- aspect of mosuo culture .
people be always fascinate by it , but misunderstanding and misperceptions abound .
one of the most common misperceptions be that the mosuo be very promiscuous , change partner all the time .
that be patently not true ; in fact , many mosuo pair will last for year , and even decade .
there be no social stigma if someone do change partner often , but it be more common for the mosuo to engage in what have be describe as " serial monogamy "...that be , they do n't stick with one partner for their whole life , but each pair will tend to last for an extended period , and they won't generally have multiple partner while in a relationship .
however , there be fascinate and very unique aspect of these walk marriage .
first , even among couple who be together for months/years/decades , they generally will never actually live together , or share property .
the man will continue to live in his family 's home , and his responsibility be to that family ; while the woman will continue to live her her home , and be responsible to her family .
the man will visit her at night , but the rest of the time they generally live separate life .
and what if they have a baby ? in general , father have little or no responsibility for children produce from such union ;
the baby will be raise in the mother 's home , and be a part of her family , not the father 's .
however , that do not mean that the men have no responsibility...it be just that the focus of that responsibility be shift .
in most culture , a man will be responsible to care for his own children ;
in mosuo culture , a man be responsible to care for the children of his sisters/nieces/aunts/etc . so mosuo men still have full parenting responsibilities...perhaps even moreso , since they may end up share responsibility for the children of many family member .
now , in some case , mosuo men do want to be involve in their own childrens ' upbringing .
if that be the case , after the child be born , the father will go to the mother 's home , and present the family matriarch with gift , ask to be accept as the father .
if the matriarch accept him , he be then an ' honorary member ' of the family , and have the right to visit and @/@ or stay there like any other family member , and to help raise the child .
however , this be not a frequent practice .
although this sound very strange at first , it actually provide remarkable stability for the children .
first , they be not raise by just one parent ; everyone in the family share in parental duty , so the child really end up have multiple father and mother figure .
furthermore , if the mother and father end their relationship , there be virtually no impact or stress for the child .
there 's no fight over split property , because they never share property .
there 's no fight over custody of the child , because the child never belong to the father to begin with .
the mother 's relationship with different men may change , but it have little or no effect on the children .
one more thing i 'd like to point out . while this system actually work very effectively for the mosuo , it work only in a situation where there be a large extend family to provide support .
for those mosuo men and women who leave home to live @/@ work on their own in other city , they almost always choose more traditional marriage .
after all , care for a baby without its father when you have 20 other people in your home to help you be one thing ;
care for a baby without its father when you live by yourself be another matter entirely .
for more information about the mosuo , their culture , and our work with them , you can check out our organization 's website . and i welcome question and comment about this , or other aspect of mosuo culture .
while their way of life hold no particular allure to me ( my job consists of sit , write on paper and think about thing , i be allergic to horse , my great joy be my western traditional family of my wife and 2 daughter ) i applaud your effort to provide as unobtrusive assistance to these people as possible .
diversity of culture and think be a good thing , and i like your organization emphasis on put them in control .
i would suggest that you do n't worry about people who suggest that you try to protect them somehow from the outside world .
if the mosuo do n't want you or your organization 's help , i be sure they be quite capable of tell you to get lose .
when you say " we " be do this , who be " we "?
in particular , have you hook up with the various group like the lsa and the endanger language foundation ?
there 's a lot -- well , by linguistics standard , a lot -- of money float around for do exactly this , and it sound like mosuo be one language that might be saveable if you can bring it to the attention of the appropriate professional .
so depending upon who the linguist you be bring in are , it may be possible @/@ practical to get some real heavyweight to come in for their support....
