are there any bridge company who 'll do a loan for an uninhabitable property ( it 's derelict )?
we need to borrow 55 % of the hammer price until we can get plan permission for restoration which will allow us to get a mortgage
( verbal approval of our plan have be give by the local plan officer and the build society in question ) .
( excuse me while i do a little - this be a build we nearly buy through normal channel 5 year ago , get gazump on and never think we 'd ever get another crack at it ! )
it do n't seem likely and would be horrendously expensive .
look at it from the lender 's point of view :
this be high risk - if you do n't get plan approval the site could actually be worth a negative amount ( due to demolition cost ) .
verbal approval be essentially worth nothing .
on the flip side there be little return for the lender as you do n't want the loan for long so not much time to charge interest .
really you would be better off : get a mortgage not a bridge loan ( also difficult ) . get an unsecured loan to buy it initially .
be aware that almost no bank or build society will give a mortgage on a property after it have be buy , if it be buy less than 6 month ago .
i do n't know the answer to your question , but it sound very risky to me .
you will be take on a costly short @-@ term loan based only on verbal promise which may not eventually come good .
what happen if the b soc do n't eventually make an offer , or it 's at a much lesser amount than you hope for ?
do it know that the house be uninhabitable - usually that make a property unmortgeable .
or if the pp take much long to be consider because there be objection / it 's refuse and you have to appeal etc ?
last time we get a thread like this , i suggest tiuta and the op do some research and find the cost be prohibitive .
i echo the other comment about how you deal with be unable to remortgage if something go wrong and would ask you to note you 'll have to stick with the bridge finance for around eight month as you won't be able to apply for the remortgage until you 've own the property for six .
caution need .
bridge be only possible where the lender believe you will live elsewhere .
they cannot lend on a property you will be live in as this then fall into fsa regulation , which bridge be exclude from .
an alternate to bridge be a non status mortgage , but the lender will still need to survey the property and carry out the nusual due dilligence to include full legal conveyancing and check .
the reason most aution deal be cash be that lend be never guarantee and can fall through at the mast moment , mean the applicant loose the property and thier 10 % deposit .
you 'll need a good deal of luck to get this through use lend .
also bridgers usualy want a clearly define exit route , and it wont be sufficient to say a remortgage should be possible subject to all manner of property repair ( what if you fall ill / go mad / get depress part way into the renovation for example ) .
