i 'd be reluctant to start mess with an elderly relative 's finance .
others in the family might accuse you of all sort when she die .
that say : 1 ) if she 's of sound mind you need to understand if she 's prepare to move from ltsb or not .
another bank may confuse her significantly .
2 ) if she want to stay with ltsb , support her in find the best home for her money from their range , but also help her to keep it in a good pay account , as most of their account have 12 month bonus .
3 ) make sure you do n't do anything with cash isa that could impact her stock and share isa .
4 ) get her agreement to shift money from the current account to a better savings account ( even if it 's only the 2 % one ) .
just because somebody 's old do n't mean that capital should be protect .
my big concern for her would be if she own a property .
there 's a high chance of an iht bill on the horizon .
i 'd be talk to an ifa about the best way to mitigate this .
as dunstonh suggest , the share will effectively be in her name and be n't relevant to the protection scheme .
this be a very tough one .
bank generally will do what 's best for them which be invariably bad for the customer .
there be a lot of evidence these be some of the worst route to market due to them often have the highest cost .
as mention though , change be never fun , especially when it could be confuse and misunderstood .
i would personally say she should find an ifa and pay upfront for advice ( ie no commission ) so she get what be most suitable for her .
given her age it 's standard practice to have less money in equity and more in guarantee income than she currently appear to have due to short term fluctuation .
