the fact that president hamid karzai have not appoint a counternarcotics minister to replace the minister who resign in july 2008 indicate the priority give to drug production even though karzai have say drug production be 1 of the most important issue for afghanistan to tackle .
very little have be do to fight corruption .
corruption feed the industry in that farmer often have to pay a 10 percent tax to afghan official or taliban insurgent .
farmer must pay various bribe .
farmer receive less than 1 @/@ 4 of the 4 billion dollar that annual trade earn which be equal to more than 1 @/@ 2 of the legal gross domestic product .
no one question how people have very low salary but drive in expensive car and live in expensive house .
typically only the courier be arrest .
oguz state bigger criminal be extremely difficult to find .
some be not live in afghanistan despite be afghans .
afghanistan 's opium be increasingly convert into heroin inside afghanistan and supply drug user in europe , central asia and the middle east .
oguz state blame afghanistan for the world 's heroin problem would be unfair as heroin production be a share responsibility .
chemical need to turn opium into heroin come primarily from the developed world and be illegally send to afghanistan .
oguz state the national strategy to deal with the drug trade should be tailor to the different circumstance in the 34 province .
13 province be declare opium @-@ free in 2007 which be double the figure from 2006 .
oguz state --
the focus should be on interdiction in southern afghanistan because of the common interest between insurgent and drug trafficker to keep the south out of reach from the government in kabul and the international aid community .
the north and center of afghanistan have more order and government structure and should be offer incentive like development to persuade farmer and other player to cease opium production .
oguz state the necessity of a long @-@ term effort to combat the drug problem with afghanistan rebuild from below @-@ scratch .
