japan ( jp )
space ; politics ; military ; technology
japan 's lower house approve bill allow use of space programs in national defense .
the legislation be the most recent effort by japan to ascribe more freedom to its tightly controlled military and would overturn a ban on the military use of space .
on 13 may 2008 japan 's powerful low house of parliament vote to allow japan 's space programs to be utilize for national defense .
the legislation be the most recent effort by japan to ascribe more freedom to the tightly controlled military technically know as a self @-@ defense force .
the legislation be expect to be approve by the upper house .
the legislation be primarily aim at permit military use of japan 's civilian @-@ control spy satellite network for defense as define by the pacifist constitution .
the bill state that space development have become increasingly important .
the bill state that space programs must contribute to ensure peace and safety of international society as well as the national security of japan .
the bill do not specify how the programs will be utilize but the satellite network and other asset could potentially be use for surveillance , plan and for a missile defense shield japan be construct with the unite state .
the bill would overturn a ban on the military use of space impose on japan 's nascent space program in 1969 .
the u.s. @-@ draft 1947 constitution prohibit japan from offensive warfare .
the legislation stipulate that all member of the cabinet and not just education , science and technology minister will be responsible for japan 's future space project .
inclusion of the defense minister in decision on space programs introduce the possibility for the military to possess and develop spy satellite .
the legislation would establish a special space task force lead by the prime minister and create the new post of space development minister .
japan 's defense agency be upgrade to ministry status in 2007 .
japanese troop be dispatch to a combat zone for the first time since world war ii in 2004 .
the mission in iraq be strictly humanitarian .
support .
both the rule coalition and the largest opposition party support the bill .
the nation 's largest newspaper yomiuri approve of the bill and urge its quick enactment .
in a weekend editorial the newspaper yomiuri state that it be logical to use space development for national security and necessary to counter the threat of north korea 's missile program .
opposition .
some pacifist lawmakers from the communist and social democratic party boycott the vote on 13 may 2008 state that the bill contradict the principle of a civilian @-@ control space program .
the leave @-@ lean newspaper asahi raise concern that the legislation could escalate friction with neighboring country .
